                                                                                                                                              [

I remember my first solo birthday—just me, a candle, and a quiet room. No gifts, no guests. Just the sound of my breath and the weight of the silence. I didn’t feel lonely, not really. I felt *seen*—not by others, but by myself. Over time, those quiet dinners with my parents became sacred. We’d sit in silence, eating the same food, talking about nothing, and in that stillness, I learned how much I carried—unseen, unspoken. I didn’t ask for help. I just *did*—cleaned, fixed, planned, carried the expectations they never said out loud. I didn’t need to prove myself. I just had to *be*. (And in that, I found independence.) I realized that being an only child didn’t mean I was isolated—it meant I learned to listen to my own voice. (I learned to trust it.) I didn’t need to fit into a family mold. I just needed to live my own truth. (And in doing so, I found peace.) I carry the weight of those expectations still, but now I carry them with balance. (I don’t hide them. I don’t ignore them. I *live* with them.) I’ve come to see that solitude isn’t emptiness—it’s space. (It’s space to grow.) And independence isn’t freedom from family—it’s freedom to choose. (It’s choosing to be whole, even when no one is watching.) In what ways does being an only child shape one’s approach to life’s challenges? (It teaches resilience. It teaches self-reliance. It teaches quiet strength.) And in relationships? (It teaches patience. It teaches listening. It teaches the courage to be alone and still be loved.)  

